{"parse":{"title":"Facial Angles (Camper)","pageid":35796957,"revid":825548206,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><caption style=\"font-style:italic;padding-bottom:0.2em;\">Facial Angles <span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Facial+Angles&amp;rft.author=%5B%5BPetrus+Camper%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=1770%2C+1791+%28engravings%29&amp;rft.pub=R.+Wild+%26+J.+Altheer%2C+%5B%5BUtrecht%5D%5D&amp;rft.pages=Original+is+a+report+of+a+few+pages%3B+the+posthumous+book+is+longer+with+notes+and+engravings\"></span></caption><tbody><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_first_page.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Petrus Camper facial angles by son Adriaan Gilles - first page.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_first_page.jpg/220px-Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_first_page.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"265\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_first_page.jpg/330px-Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_first_page.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_first_page.jpg/440px-Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_first_page.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"665\" data-file-height=\"800\" /></a><div>1791 posthumous edition by Camper's son</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Author</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Petrus_Camper\" title=\"Petrus Camper\">Petrus Camper</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Original&#160;title</th><td>\n<i><small>Report of the content of two lectures (Dutch: </small></i><small>Berigt van den zaaklyken inhoud van twee lessen<i>)</i></small></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Illustrator</th><td>\nPetrus Camper, engraved by <a href=\"/wiki/Reinier_Vinkeles\" title=\"Reinier Vinkeles\">Reinier Vinkeles</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Country</th><td>\nNetherlands</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Language</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Dutch_language\" title=\"Dutch language\">Dutch</a>, French</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Subject</th><td>\nFacial angles in portraiture through the centuries</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Genre</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Art_History\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Art History\">Art History</a>, Drawing lessons</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Publisher</th><td>\nR. Wild &amp; J. Altheer, <a href=\"/wiki/Utrecht\" title=\"Utrecht\">Utrecht</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><div style=\"padding:0.1em 0;line-height:1.2em;\">Publication date</div></th><td>\n1770, 1791 (engravings)</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Media&#160;type</th><td>\nPrint (<a href=\"/wiki/Hardcover\" title=\"Hardcover\">Hardcover</a>), Online version of original text available from the <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_library_for_Dutch_literature\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Digital library for Dutch literature\">DBNL</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Google_books\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Google books\">Google books</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Pages</th><td>\nOriginal is a report of a few pages; the posthumous book is longer with notes and engravings</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Facial Angles</b> refers to the content of two lectures on this subject by the Amsterdam professor of anatomy <a href=\"/wiki/Petrus_Camper\" title=\"Petrus Camper\">Petrus Camper</a> on the 1st and 8 August in 1770 to the Amsterdam Drawing Academy called the <i>Teken-akademie</i>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Background\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Background</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#On_traditional_drawing_lessons\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">On traditional drawing lessons</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#A_new_drawing_method_based_on_facial_angle\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">A new drawing method based on facial angle</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Legacy\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Legacy</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Background\">Background</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Facial_Angles_(Camper)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Background\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Camper was a competent artist and draughtsman who had taken drawing lessons from <a href=\"/wiki/Carel_de_Moor\" title=\"Carel de Moor\">Carel de Moor</a> and his son <a href=\"/wiki/Carel_Isaak_de_Moor\" title=\"Carel Isaak de Moor\">Carel Isaak de Moor</a> in Leiden, and whose own pupils had been <a href=\"/wiki/Martin_van_Marum\" title=\"Martin van Marum\">Martin van Marum</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Johannes_le_Francq_van_Berkhey\" title=\"Johannes le Francq van Berkhey\">Johannes le Francq van Berkhey</a>, and <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Wibrand_Veltman&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Wibrand Veltman (page does not exist)\">Wibrand Veltman</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> His broad interest in the natural sciences had led him to anatomy and he was praelector of the Amsterdam Surgeon's guild, a respected position that placed him also in the Amsterdam <i>vroedschap</i> or regency. He had published papers and lectures on a variety of anatomy subjects, and came to the lectures with several engraved examples of popular art that he wanted to discuss on the basis of anatomy. He brought with him the skull of a baby, child, man, and elderly man, and two large canvasses with sketched drawings of the mathematical dimensions of the human head.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"On_traditional_drawing_lessons\">On traditional drawing lessons</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Facial_Angles_(Camper)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: On traditional drawing lessons\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Jean-Baptiste_Greuze_-_Retour_sur_soi-m%C3%AAme.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Jean-Baptiste_Greuze_-_Retour_sur_soi-m%C3%AAme.jpg/220px-Jean-Baptiste_Greuze_-_Retour_sur_soi-m%C3%AAme.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"203\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Jean-Baptiste_Greuze_-_Retour_sur_soi-m%C3%AAme.jpg/330px-Jean-Baptiste_Greuze_-_Retour_sur_soi-m%C3%AAme.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Jean-Baptiste_Greuze_-_Retour_sur_soi-m%C3%AAme.jpg/440px-Jean-Baptiste_Greuze_-_Retour_sur_soi-m%C3%AAme.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"670\" data-file-height=\"618\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Jean-Baptiste_Greuze_-_Retour_sur_soi-m%C3%AAme.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><a href=\"/wiki/Jean-Baptiste_Greuze\" title=\"Jean-Baptiste Greuze\">Greuze</a>'s \"Retour sur soi-m\u00eame\" was an example of a bad likeness of the head of an old woman, because classical drawing theory was applied which was based on a young adult male's head. Merely adding wrinkles and a costume cannot help a poor likeness.</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Jan_de_Visscher-_de_moor.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Jan_de_Visscher-_de_moor.jpg/220px-Jan_de_Visscher-_de_moor.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"261\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Jan_de_Visscher-_de_moor.jpg/330px-Jan_de_Visscher-_de_moor.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Jan_de_Visscher-_de_moor.jpg/440px-Jan_de_Visscher-_de_moor.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1200\" data-file-height=\"1426\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Jan_de_Visscher-_de_moor.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><i>The Moor</i>, an etching by <a href=\"/wiki/Jan_de_Visscher\" title=\"Jan de Visscher\">Jan de Visscher</a> after a drawing by his brother <a href=\"/wiki/Cornelis_Visscher\" title=\"Cornelis Visscher\">Cornelis</a></div></div></div>\n<p>Camper's main points in his first lecture were that classical drawing lessons from the time of <i><a href=\"/wiki/Vitruvius\" title=\"Vitruvius\">Vitruvius</a></i>, including the teachings of <i><a href=\"/wiki/Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer\" title=\"Albrecht D\u00fcrer\">D\u00fcrer</a></i> and <i><a href=\"/wiki/Charles_Perrault\" title=\"Charles Perrault\">Perreault</a></i>, were based on an incorrect assumption that the human head was oval at all ages, and he proceeded to prove this with his dimensions of the skulls. He also remarked that none of the various humans of modern \"nations\" such as Europeans, <a href=\"/wiki/Moors\" title=\"Moors\">Moors</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Kalmyk_people\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Kalmyk people\">Kalmyk</a> people adhere to the classic form of head so remarkable in Grecian sculpture. The travelogues of <i><a href=\"/wiki/Pliny_the_Elder\" title=\"Pliny the Elder\">Plinius</a></i> and <i><a href=\"/wiki/Georges_Louis_Leclerc,_Count_of_Buffon\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Georges Louis Leclerc, Count of Buffon\">de Buffon</a></i> made mention of practises in infancy which caused these national characteristics, such as Chinese women pulling their eye lids to the sides, or African Moors pressing their noses flat, or Europeans pressing their ears flat with caps tied tight. Camper claimed this was all nonsense and the forms of people's faces (and their skulls) were related to their living environments. He then proceeded to demonstrate on his sketches, by shortening the chin he could transform a likeness of a man to an old man, and by adjusting the facial angle, he changed a Moor into a European, and he was so successful in this demonstration with a few lines of chalk, that the hall cheered.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"A_new_drawing_method_based_on_facial_angle\">A new drawing method based on facial angle</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Facial_Angles_(Camper)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: A new drawing method based on facial angle\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>His first lecture had dwelled on the skull's form among ages and among these three nations, and the second lecture (which was so well populated by students that the hall proved too small) was intended as a practical guide how to better make portraits that looked like the subject. For this he brought with him more sketches in the same dimensions as the first two that by means of arrangement along the dimension lines could be easily compared for sketching. He discussed the classical facial angle using the plaster cast of Apollo that was in the lecture hall.\n</p><p>The artist-collector <a href=\"/wiki/Cornelis_Ploos_van_Amstel\" title=\"Cornelis Ploos van Amstel\">Cornelis Ploos van Amstel</a> first published notes on Camper's lectures in the Leiden literature society proceedings in 1770 in which a book was promised with engravings, and though <a href=\"/wiki/Reinier_Vinkeles\" title=\"Reinier Vinkeles\">Reinier Vinkeles</a> made engravings for this purpose in 1785, a book was only posthumously published by Camper's son <a href=\"/wiki/Adriaan_Gilles_Camper\" title=\"Adriaan Gilles Camper\">Adriaan Gilles Camper</a> in 1791 after Camper senior died.\n</p>\n<ul class=\"gallery mw-gallery-traditional\">\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:37px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_baby_to_old_man.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_baby_to_old_man.jpg/120px-Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_baby_to_old_man.jpg\" width=\"120\" height=\"76\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_baby_to_old_man.jpg/180px-Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_baby_to_old_man.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_baby_to_old_man.jpg/240px-Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_baby_to_old_man.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"720\" data-file-height=\"455\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>...<i>On the first canvas the head of a child, the head of an adult man, and the head of an old man were shown with their skulls above them, all in profile</i>...\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:36.5px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_orangutan_to_moor.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_orangutan_to_moor.jpg/120px-Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_orangutan_to_moor.jpg\" width=\"120\" height=\"77\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_orangutan_to_moor.jpg/180px-Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_orangutan_to_moor.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_orangutan_to_moor.jpg/240px-Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_orangutan_to_moor.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"720\" data-file-height=\"460\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>...<i> the second canvas had the heads of two apes, an African Moor and a Kalmyk or Asian, again with their skulls drawn above them...</i>\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:36.5px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_europeaan_tot_antiek.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_europeaan_tot_antiek.jpg/120px-Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_europeaan_tot_antiek.jpg\" width=\"120\" height=\"77\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_europeaan_tot_antiek.jpg/180px-Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_europeaan_tot_antiek.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_europeaan_tot_antiek.jpg/240px-Petrus_Camper_facial_angles_by_son_Adriaan_Gilles_-_europeaan_tot_antiek.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"720\" data-file-height=\"460\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>..<i>and again a canvas was brought out with three heads next to each other in profile with varying facial angles; 80 degrees, 90 degrees, and 100 degrees</i>...\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Apollo_Belvedere_2.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/27/Apollo_Belvedere_2.jpg/90px-Apollo_Belvedere_2.jpg\" width=\"90\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/27/Apollo_Belvedere_2.jpg/135px-Apollo_Belvedere_2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/27/Apollo_Belvedere_2.jpg/180px-Apollo_Belvedere_2.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2304\" data-file-height=\"3072\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>The <i>Apollo Pythias</i>, a plaster cast of which was in the lecture hall.\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Legacy\">Legacy</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Facial_Angles_(Camper)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Legacy\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Bernard_Picart_-_Sophocles_Medusa_-_Philipp_von_Stosch_-_Pierres_antiques_grav%C3%A9es.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Bernard_Picart_-_Sophocles_Medusa_-_Philipp_von_Stosch_-_Pierres_antiques_grav%C3%A9es.png/220px-Bernard_Picart_-_Sophocles_Medusa_-_Philipp_von_Stosch_-_Pierres_antiques_grav%C3%A9es.png\" width=\"220\" height=\"320\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Bernard_Picart_-_Sophocles_Medusa_-_Philipp_von_Stosch_-_Pierres_antiques_grav%C3%A9es.png/330px-Bernard_Picart_-_Sophocles_Medusa_-_Philipp_von_Stosch_-_Pierres_antiques_grav%C3%A9es.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Bernard_Picart_-_Sophocles_Medusa_-_Philipp_von_Stosch_-_Pierres_antiques_grav%C3%A9es.png/440px-Bernard_Picart_-_Sophocles_Medusa_-_Philipp_von_Stosch_-_Pierres_antiques_grav%C3%A9es.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"550\" data-file-height=\"800\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Bernard_Picart_-_Sophocles_Medusa_-_Philipp_von_Stosch_-_Pierres_antiques_grav%C3%A9es.png\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The \"monstrous\" Medusa with 100 degree facial angle</div></div></div>\n<p>Camper's work was later quoted again and again, and his engraved drawings were used to prove that he had tried to show a hierarchy of facial angles from the orangutan to the European, but this was never part of either of the two lectures. In fact, he was only trying to help artists make better portraits, and remarked that of all the great masters of art that can be observed in engravings such as <i><a href=\"/wiki/Rubens\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Rubens\">Rubens</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Anthony_van_Dyck\" title=\"Anthony van Dyck\">van Dyk</a></i>, and <i><a href=\"/wiki/Jacob_Jordaens\" title=\"Jacob Jordaens\">Jordaans</a></i> only the Haarlemmer <a href=\"/wiki/Cornelis_Visscher\" title=\"Cornelis Visscher\">Cornelis Visscher</a> had ever been able to draw the head of a Moor correctly.\n</p><p>Though <a href=\"/wiki/Georges_Cuvier\" title=\"Georges Cuvier\">Georges Cuvier</a> felt that Camper's sketches showed the superiority of the white man in beauty as being the closest to the Classic ideal, this was against the views of Camper. Camper claimed that both edges of the spectrum were monsters, which is to say that orangutans and apes (with facial angle 42-50 degrees) were just as ugly as Sophocles' <a href=\"/wiki/Medusa\" title=\"Medusa\">Medusa</a> engraved in profile by <a href=\"/wiki/Bernard_Picart\" title=\"Bernard Picart\">Bernard Picart</a> for <a href=\"/wiki/Philipp_von_Stosch\" title=\"Philipp von Stosch\">Philipp von Stosch</a>'s \"Pierres Antiques Grav\u00e9es\". The facial angles of Moors and Kalmyks was calculated to be 70 degrees, and that of a European 80 degrees.\n</p><p>The original report of these lectures in the proceedings of the literature society is listed as one of the 1000 most important texts in the <a href=\"/wiki/Canon_of_Dutch_Literature\" title=\"Canon of Dutch Literature\">Canon of Dutch Literature</a>.\n</p>\n<table role=\"presentation\" class=\"mbox-small plainlinks sistersitebox\" style=\"background-color:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;color:#000\">\n<tbody><tr>\n<td class=\"mbox-image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/30px-Commons-logo.svg.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"40\" class=\"noviewer\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/45px-Commons-logo.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/59px-Commons-logo.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1024\" data-file-height=\"1376\" /></td>\n<td class=\"mbox-text plainlist\">Wikimedia Commons has media related to <i><b><a href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Facial_angles_(Camper)\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"commons:Category:Facial angles (Camper)\">Facial angles (Camper)</a></b></i>.</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Facial_Angles_(Camper)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://rkd.nl/en/explore/artists/90470\">Petrus Camper</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/RKD\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"RKD\">RKD</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=G-oEAAAAQAAJ\">Vaderlandse Oefeningen, 1770 (Google Books)</a>, report by Cornelis Ploos van Amstel, pp 386-393</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<ul><li><i>Verhandeling van Petrus Camper over het natuurlijk verschil der wezenstrekken in menschen van onderscheiden landaart en ouderdom; over het schoon in antyke beelden en gesneedene steenen. Gevolgd door een voorstel van eene nieuwe manier om hoofden van allerleye menschen met zekerheid te tekenen. Naa des Schrijvers dood uitgegeven door zijnen zoon Adriaan Gilles Camper</i>, 1791 (<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.earlydutchbooksonline.nl/nl/view/image/id/dpo%3A1325%3Ampeg21%3A0005/searchvalue/\">text and engravings</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Koninklijke_Bibliotheek,_National_Library_of_the_Netherlands\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Koninklijke Bibliotheek, National Library of the Netherlands\">Koninklijke Bibliotheek</a>)</li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2198\nCached time: 20180921033111\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usa